title: For Sale:  Civil War  Smith carbine .50 cal
postcontent:
The Smith Carbine was a 0.50 caliber breech-loading rifle patented by Gilbert Smith on June 23, 1857 and successfully completed the Military Trials of the late 1850s. It was used by various cavalry units during the American Civil War.

The Smith Carbine was unique in that it broke apart in the middle for loading and it used rubber cartridges which sealed the gases in the breech. The downside was that these cartridges were difficult to remove.[1]

The carbines were built by Massachusetts Arms Company of Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts; the American Machine Works in Springfield, Massachusetts; or the American Arms Company in Chicopee Falls. The name of the distributor for the manufacturer, Poultney & Trimble of Baltimore, Maryland, is often stamped on the carbine's receivers.  only 30,062 made.

ABOUT THE GUN-  The one you are viewing does show its age with a lot of patina and light  pitting on the barrel and receiver. There is a little pitting in the bore but nothing that should effect accuracy. All serial numbers match though out the gun, The action locks up tight no side movement at the breach, action works smoothly. stock is solid, does indicate that the gun was used as a club do to 2 light cracks on either side of the stock. There are what appears to be counting marks on the side of the fore stock, maybe a account of confederates taken with the gun? This gun shows obvious signs of being in the war and lots of use. Very cool gun to have in your collection. 
 Will sell face to face (you travel) or will ship but to ffl only   buyer pays shipping. pay pal, m.o, or visa/master debit card excepted.
 please include a contact phone number, for some reason return emails don't get sent.

title: For Sale:  Magnum Research BFR 454 Casull
postcontent:
I have a like new Magnum Research BFR 454 Casull for sale.  The gun is super nice, very well made and powerful, I purchased it brand new.  For those unfamiliar with these revolvers, the frames are cast by the same place that does Ruger single actions, but they're fit and finish is nicer than Rugers.  The rear sight even has the Ruger logo on it, so this is essentially a more robust Super Blackhawk with better fit and finish, and better features too.

It's got an unfluted cylinder that has a free spinning pawl so it spins in either direction (Ruger for example only spins clockwise), and the chambers are recessed as well.  It's a flat top and is drilled and tapped for scope use and comes with the factory scope mount.  It also comes standard with an over sized locking base pin.  The trigger is excellent as well.

The barrel is 7.5" long and is hand lapped from the factory, it's a 5 shot and very, very strong.  To those somewhat familiar with single actions, the BFR is somewhere in between a Ruger and a Freedom Arms in terms of quality.  This gun has been shot about 20 times, that's it and it has been very well taken care of, no nicks or scrapes on it and cleaned after each use.

Buds sells these for about $935, after taxes you're at $1000.  I'm asking $750 for it and a soft hoslter.  The gun is as close to brand new as it gets.  I'm not really looking to trade right now, so if I don't respond to your trade request don't take it personal.  I live around Danville and will meet up with you as long as it's reasonable.  Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale/Trade:  FM HiPower Hi Power M95 Classic
postcontent:
FM Hipower clone, not to be confused with the FEG clones that were imported around the same time, but at a much lower quality.  The FM is a high quality Argentinian Browning Hi Power clone, and all of the Browning parts are interchangeable with the FM.  The Classic is fairly rare, and masterfully done, and features many of the same features as the model III Browning Hi Powers.  
  Comes with factory magazine, though any magazine for the browning hi power will work and operate with this weapon.  There is very little wear on this firearm, and the slide and magazine release is very positive.  The magazine that comes with it is not drop-free, but it will drop free with other browning high-power magazines.  
  This is a soft shooter, and points intuitively, and has very mild and manageable recoil.  There aren't very many of these in the states, due to the dropping price of the dollar during the importation.  If you would like to try before you buy, I would be more than happy to meet at Talon or another reputable range.  
(I put Browning as the manufacturer because this is closer to a Browning in terms of quality than an FEG, but this firearm is an FM.)

  Thank you for looking!

title: For Sale:  Gen 3 Mossberg 930 SPX Custom *READ*
location: Columbus, Canal Winchester, Lancaster, etc., Columbus, Ohio
postcontent:
This is a Gen 3 (about 7 months old) 930 SPX.  I've gone through about five of these shotguns (one Gen 1, two Gen 2's, and two Gen 3's) looking for "the one" that would actually be what Mossberg claimed the 930 SPX should be...and a little more (like cycle weak loads under 1200fps).  

I found all that in this 930.  It was broken in as per Mossberg's instructions with heavy loads and reliably cycles Wal-Mart light bird shot all the way up to 3" big boys.  After break-in it was sent for some custom work.  

It has a polished trigger job, enlarged feed port, the bolt and bolt carrier have been de-burred everywhere, a Mesa 930 Urbino shortened LOP stock was installed, the recoil spring was micro polished and lightly greased with NyoGel, the recoil plunger was radiused for smooth action, and it has been re-coated in Magpul Tan KG-2400 (a far superior coating than Cerakote).  This gal is ready for anything, it's low maintenance (all coated parts do not require oil), and runs like a top.  It has NONE of the issues that the few 930 SPX's that crept past Mossberg's QC have had in the past.  It's probably one of the fastest cycling 930's you'll find anywhere. 

...All that and my fickle mind has gone a different direction (haha, I can't never decide on just one).  I've found a smoking deal on a Beretta 1301 Comp that I gotta have but can't justify so this bad girl's gotta go.  

The original stock, recoil action tube, recoil/action spring, butt pad, sling, and original box/paperwork/lock, etc. will also be included as if purchased new.  I will also include the Trijicon ACOG Reflex that's pictured with it.  Before you get all excited the ACOG ain't perfect.  It's been to the desert quite a few times (it's probably 10years old) and suffered from all the same problems as every other ACOG Reflex I've ever had (washes out in a lot of light.....not good for the desert).  My unit Armorer played with our all of our teams ACOG's and made them a little better but we still swapped out to TA31F's and COMP M4's.  I will never use it so it's yours to play with.  A $550 Reflex for free ain't a bad deal either way you look at it.  It is NOT included in the price so don't ask for a different price on the 930 without it included.  If you don't want the ACOG I'll put it back on the shelf.  

The smith work and stock cost total about what this gun sells for retail.  Anyone that knows anything can tell you that.  This ain't your off-the-shelf SPX so don't low ball me, the price is more than fair.  Honestly, this is how the 930's should come out of the box (they'd just cost twice as much).  Everything is still serviceable so if anything every gets worn out all parts can still be ordered from Mossberg.

If I had to classify this 930 as it sits right now I'd put it in line with the FN SLP MK1 Tactical.  It's every bit as fast and smooth as my FN but without the cost (well, cost to you anyway). 

Call or text 614-five3one-61five9

I will meet anyone on the East Side of Columbus, Pickerington, Canal Winchester, Carroll, Baltimore, Millersport, Groveport, Grove City, or Lancaster...Maybe even Hebron or Heath/Newark.
